Here's the recommended approach using `Window` lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

**1. Create a custom Window subclass in `App.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new AppWindow(new AppShell());
}

public class AppWindow : Window
{
    public AppWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        // Save draft when app is backgrounded
        if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", note.ViewModel.DraftText);
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        // Restore draft when app returns
        if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
            note.ViewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
        if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", note.ViewModel.DraftText);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`OnStopped`** — fires when the app is fully backgrounded (not visible). Save here.
- **`OnResumed`** — fires when returning from background. Restore here.
- **`OnDestroying`** — also save here because Android's back button can skip `Stopped`.
- **Keep handlers fast** (< 1–2 seconds) — `Preferences` is ideal for small string values. Avoid database writes in lifecycle handlers.
- **Don't save in `OnDeactivated`** — that fires for dialogs/notification shade, not necessarily backgrounding.
